<h1>Dicentra peregrina – Japanese Alpine Bleeding Heart</h1>

<p>
<a href="/o/page?o=word&w=Bleeding%20Heart">Bleeding Heart</a> peregrina is a rare alpine species adapted to cold, rocky mountain environments in East Asia.
</p>

<h2>Description</h2>
<p>
A compact, low-growing plant with finely divided leaves and small pink to magenta heart-shaped flowers.
</p>

<h2>Etymology</h2>
<p>
“Peregrina” means “wanderer” or “foreign,” reflecting its alpine and isolated habitat.
</p>

<h2>Taxonomy</h2>
<p>
Family: Papaveraceae<br>
Genus: Dicentra<br>
Species: D. peregrina
</p>

<h2>Distribution and Habitat</h2>
<p>
Native to Japan and parts of northeastern Asia, found in alpine scree and rocky slopes.
</p>

<h2>Ecology</h2>
<p>
Adapted to cold, high-altitude conditions with a short growing season; pollinated by small insects.
</p>

<h2>Cultivation</h2>
<ul>
<li>Cool alpine conditions</li>
<li>Well-drained, gritty soil</li>
<li>Protected from heat and humidity</li>
</ul>

<h3>Cultivars</h3>
<ul>
<li>Mostly wild type in cultivation</li>
</ul>

<h2>Symbolism</h2>
<p>
Represents rarity, endurance, and quiet resilience in harsh landscapes.
</p>

